Quantitative analysis of chlorophyll spectroscopic data: Differentiating Chl a and Chl f¶

Author: Hao-Li Huang
Date modified: Feb 13, 2021
Data sets: 6kmx, cone 1 and cone 3, formyl params, sharpened ESP

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Chlorophyll, Cryo-EM, and PSI¶

Chlorophylls are the green molecules used by photosynthetic organisms to harvest solar energy. They are also responsible for the green color of many plants, algae, and cyanobacteria.

The most common kind of chlorophyll is chlorophyll a. In this analysis, however, we are interested in another kind of chlorophyll, chlorophyll f, which is found in far-red light adapted cyanobacteria, because chlorophyll f can absorb redder wavelengths compared to chlorophyll a.

The two kinds of chlorophylls are extremely similar. The only difference is a methyl group in chl a being substituted by a formyl group. In other words, a hydrogen is substituted by an oxygen.

Figures in the introduction courtesy of Dr. Chris Gisriel, Dr. Jimin Wang, and David Flesher.

In [2]:
Image('chl_comparison.jpg')
Out[2]:

Cryogenic electron microscopy (cryo-EM) can determine high-resolution structures of biomolecules in solution. It reports the electrostatic potential in the space, which then can be used to model the structure.

Below is a structure of photosystem I (PSI), which is a protein complex part of photosynthesis, in a far-red light (FRL) adapted cyanobacterium, with chlorophylls highlighted in green.

In [3]:
Image('PSI.jpg')
Out[3]:

Although the chls can be reliably identified in the Cryo-EM maps, the assignment of chl a and chl f is uncertain. In this analysis, we are interested in figuring out which of the chls above are chl f. This structural knowledge will help us understand the energetic landscape of the energy transfer in the protein complex.

The method we use here is called 'cone scan', first described by my colleagues Chris Gisriel and Jimin Wang (published in Commucations Biology, https://doi.org/10.1038/s42003-020-01139-1). We look at the cone 1 and cone 3 positions of the chl, shown in the figure below. Cone 3 would be a methyl for both chl a and f, whereas cone 1 would be a methyl for chl a and formyl for chl f. Because oxygen of formyl groups is larger than hydrogen of methyl groups, the oxygen should have a larger electrostatic potential. We know the bond length of a C=O double bond and the C-C=O angle, so the possible location of the oxygen is the dashed circle in the figure. (i.e. The dihedral angle of the C-C=O and the porpherin can vary.) The scan around the C-C bond forms a cone shape, thus the name of 'cone scan'.

1.2 Objective¶

The goal of this analysis is to identify possible chlorophyll f using the Cryo-EM ESP map of the FRL-PSI structure (protein databank id: 6kmx).

Becuase cone 3 is always methyl, we take it as the internal reference of the chlorophylls. The cone 3 scans gives us a baseline of how a methyl ESP looks like. Then, we take the cone 1 scan traces to see if they are similar to this baseline. If a trace is not similar to the baseline, it is likely that it is not a methyl, but a formyl substituent, thus a chl f.

def load_data(dirs):
    df = pd.DataFrame([])
    for i, d in enumerate(dirs):
        data = np.loadtxt(d, delimiter=' ')
        # Extract chl id from file names
        chl_id = re.findall('([A-Z]\d{3})_', d)[0].lower()
        # Column name: chl id; column values: electrostatic potentials
        df[chl_id] = data[:,1]
    # Index: scan angles
    angle = data[:,0].astype(int)
    df = df.set_index(angle)
    
    return df

def plot_hist_norm(ax, df, row, xlim, label = None, 
                   bar_color = 'tab:blue', curve_color = 'blue'):
    
    x = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 100)   # x range for normal fitting
    bins = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 15) # bin positions for histogram
    degrees = df.index                       # degrees for subplot title
    
    # Plot histogram
    ax.hist(df.iloc[row], bins=bins, density=True, alpha=0.7, color=bar_color, label=label)
    ax.axvline(0, c='black', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    
    ### Normal fitting
    parameters = norm.fit(df.iloc[row])
    # now, parameters[0] and parameters[1] are the mean and 
    # the standard deviation of the fitted distribution
    # Generate the pdf (fitted distribution)
    fitted_pdf = norm.pdf(x,loc = parameters[0],scale = parameters[1])
    
    # Plot Gaussian fit
    ax.plot(x,fitted_pdf,curve_color,linestyle="dashed", linewidth=2)
    ax.set_xlabel('Electrostatic Potential')
    ax.set_ylabel('Probability Density')
    ax.set_title(str(degrees[row].astype(int)) + ' degrees')
    if label:
        ax.legend(loc=1)

def plot_cones(ax, Y_cone1, Y_cone3):
    ### Plot traces, one chl at a time
    X = Y_cone1.index
    ax.plot(X, Y_cone1, c='navy')
    ax.plot(X, Y_cone3, c='darkgreen')

    # Plot the mean values of the traces as horizontal lines
    ax.axhline(np.mean(Y_cone1), c='navy', linestyle='dotted', alpha=0.7)
    ax.axhline(np.mean(Y_cone3), c='darkgreen', linestyle='dotted', alpha=0.7)
    
    # Plot y=0
    ax.axhline(0, c='black', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    ax.set_xlim([0, 355])
    ax.set_xlabel('Dihedral Angle (deg)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Electrostatic Potential')

def plot_meanstd(ax, mean, std, n, c_mean='tab:orange', c_fill='tab:orange'):
    # mean is a df with scan angles as index and mean of each angle as value
    X = mean.index
    ax.plot(X, mean, c=c_mean, label='Cone 3 mean')
    ax.fill_between(X, mean+std*n, mean-std*n, alpha=0.3, 
                    color=c_fill, label=str(n) + ' standard deviations')

In [12]:
def standardized_signal(c1, c3):
    stdrdz_sig = pd.DataFrame([])
    ### Get mean and std in each resolution bin
    for b in (unique_bin):
        chl_id = res[res['bin'] == b].index
        mean = c3[chl_id].mean(1)
        std = c3[chl_id].std(1)
        # Calculate standardized signals and put them in stdrdz_sig
        stdrdz_sig[chl_id] = c1[chl_id].apply(lambda col: (col-mean)/std)

    # Replace negative values to np.nan for easier presentation
    stdrdz_sig = stdrdz_sig.applymap(lambda x: x if x > 0 else np.NaN)
    
    # Temporarily append a row containing the max of each column for sorting purpose
    stdrdz_sig = stdrdz_sig.append(pd.Series(stdrdz_sig.max(), name = 'max'))
    stdrdz_sig = stdrdz_sig.sort_values(by='max', ascending=False, axis=1)
    
    # Drop the 'max' row and transpose for visualization
    stdrdz_sig = stdrdz_sig.drop('max').T
    
    return stdrdz_sig

def chl_heatmap(chl_sig, title, cbar_size=1):
    plt.subplots(figsize=(6,chl_sig.shape[0]*0.4))
    ### Plot heatmap
    g = sns.heatmap(chl_sig, cmap='Greens', cbar_kws={"shrink": cbar_size})
    
    ### Format tick lables
    plt.setp(g.get_yticklabels(), rotation=0)
    # Color ytick labels according to resolution bin
    for i, tick_label in enumerate(g.axes.get_yticklabels()):
        if res.loc[chl_sig.index[i],'res'] <= 2.4:
            tick_label.set_color('g')
        elif res.loc[chl_sig.index[i],'res'] <= 2.6:
            tick_label.set_color('y')
        else:
            tick_label.set_color('r')
    g.set(xticks=np.arange(0, 72, 12))
    g.set(xticklabels=np.arange(0, 360, 60))
    plt.setp(g.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
    
    g.set_ylabel('Chlorophyll ID')
    g.set_xlabel('Dihedral Angle (deg)')
    g = plt.title(title)

def highlight_traces_bin(Y1, Y3, title, n_std):
    ### Plot baseline (cone 3) of each bin
    l = len(unique_bin) # number of bins
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(3,l,figsize=(l*3, 10), sharex=True, sharey=True)
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=16)
    axs = axs.ravel()
    
    ### Get the chl ids to highlight
    stdrdz_sig = standardized_signal(c1, c3)
    highlight = (stdrdz_sig - n_std).applymap(lambda c: 
                                    c if c > 0 else np.nan).dropna(how='all').index
    
    ## Plot each bin
    X = Y1.index
    for j in range(l):
        # chl id in this bin
        chl_id = res[res['bin']==unique_bin[j]].index 
        
        chl_hl = chl_id.intersection(highlight)  # chl ids to highlight in this bin
        chl_nonhl = chl_id.difference(highlight) # chl ids to not highlight
        
        y1h = c1[chl_hl]    # Cone 1 traces to highlight in this bin
        y1n = c1[chl_nonhl] # Cone 1 traces to not highlight
        y1 = c1[chl_id]     # All cone 1 traces
        y3 = c3[chl_id]     # All cone 3 traces
        
        # First row: Cone 3 with mean and n_std standard deviations
        plot_data(axs[j], X, y3, 12)
        plot_meanstd(axs[j], y3.mean(1), y3.std(1), n_std)
        axs[j].set_title(str(unique_bin[j]) + ', cone 3')

        # Second row: Cone 1 with mean
        plot_data(axs[j+l], X, y1n, 12, 'tab:gray')    # Not highlight
        axs[j+l].plot(X, y1.mean(1), c='tab:green')
        plot_data(axs[j+l], X, y1h, 12, 'tab:red')     # Highlight
        axs[j+l].set_title(str(unique_bin[j]) + ', cone 1')

        # Third row: Cone 1 masked
        plot_data(axs[j+l*2], X, y1n, 12, 'tab:gray')  # Not highlight
        plot_meanstd(axs[j+l*2], y3.mean(1), y3.std(1), n_std, 'tab:blue', 'tab:blue')
        plot_data(axs[j+l*2], X, y1h, 12, 'tab:red')   # Highlight
        axs[j+l*2].set_title(str(unique_bin[j]) + ', cone 1, masked')

    for ax in axs.flat:
        ax.label_outer()
    fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.91)

4. Possible Chlorophyll f's¶

I tried to identify a small group of traces that are disimilar to the rest using two methods. First, I used the Gaussian Mixture Model to cluster the traces into three groups, one big group corresponding to Chl a, and two small groups to Chl f. Second, I identified the traces with large peak values by comparing them with the baseline level derived using cone 3.

4.1 Gaussian Mixture Model¶

Clustering using Gaussian Mixture Model. The underlying assumption here is that the shape of the cone 1 trace of a methyl substituent would look different from that of a formyl substitutent. In addition, there should be two groups of formyl traces, with the oxygen pointing towards 0 and 180 degrees. Thus, the number of components in the Gaussian Mixture Model is set to be 3. The outcome may be different depending on the random initialization.

In [24]:
def plot_gaussian_mixture(X, random_state=None):
    X = X.T
    ### Gaussian mixture model. Because the 'full' covariance type leads
    ### to overfitting, here we choose to use 'tied'.
    gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=3, random_state=random_state,
                          n_init=50, covariance_type='tied').fit(X)
    pred = gmm.predict(X)

    ### Sort clusters. Second largest cluster called group 1, and 
    ### smallest cluster called group 2. These two groups likely
    ### correspond to formyl substituents
    count = (np.count_nonzero(pred==0), np.count_nonzero(pred==1), 
             np.count_nonzero(pred==2))
    cat = sorted(range(len(count)), key=count.__getitem__, reverse=True)

    rest = X[pred==cat[0]]
    group1 = X[pred==cat[1]]
    group2 = X[pred==cat[2]]

    ### Plot clusters
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 6))
    ax.plot(rest.T.index, rest.T, color='grey')
    ax.plot(group1.T.index, group1.T, color='red')
    ax.plot(group2.T.index, group2.T, color='blue')
    ax.axhline(0, c='black', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    ax.set_xlim([0, 355])
    ax.set_xlabel('Dihedral Angle (deg)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Electrostatic Potential');
    
    print('group 1 (red): {}'.format(list(X[pred==cat[1]].index)))
    print('group 2 (blue): {}'.format(list(X[pred==cat[2]].index)))

4.2 Identifying Traces with Large Peak Values¶

Three resolution bins, cut off at 2.4 and 2.6 angstroms¶

The chlorophylls are first split into resolution bins, and then passed into the function standardized_signal. The output corresponds to how many standard deviations the cone 1 signal is above the mean of the cone 3 signal.

$$ \mathrm{\frac{Signal(cone\ 1)-Mean(cone\ 3)}{SD(cone\ 3)}} $$
The mean and standard deviation are only taken from the cone 3 signals in the corresponding resolution bin.
Here I only keep the positive values and replace the negative ones with NaN (not a number).

In [28]:

In the last row, we compare the cone 1 traces with the mean of cone 3 (orange line) and 3 standard deviations of cone 3 (orange shade), which defines the baseline level in this analysis. The cone 1 traces that sticks out of the orange shade is considered dissimilar to methyl data. These chls are listed in the heatmap below. The label color corresponds to the resolution bin. Green is the highest resolution, yellow middle, and red lowest. The heatmap shows how many standard deviations this cone 1 signal sticks out of the baseline.

However, due to the inherent difficulties of identifying single atoms using Cryo-EM, definitive assignments can't be made using these analysis alone. Other indirect evidence are needed to help identify Chl f. However, this method provides a quantitative way to pick out possible candidtates for Chl f.

It is worth mentioning that 66% of the possible Chl f's identified by these methods are consistent with those that are already suggested by other evidence to be Chl f's (more details in the manuscript, to be updated upon publication). This demonstrates that the quantitative analyses do produce consistent and sensible results, albeit the mediocre data quality (resulted from the structural resolution).
